T7	h3 879 903	The case of South Africa
T8	p 904 1570	South Africa decreases in number of interceptions, but keep in mind that the bulk of its exports began in September and that it has suspended exports of oranges from its areas with pests, though not the others. Despite suspending these shipments, it has still accumulated 16 interceptions so far this year, 4 of them in September, "which shows once again that it does not meet its commitments." Of these 16 interceptions, 13 correspond to the Phyllosticta citricarpa, a fungus that causes the dreaded citrus black spot disease. In this sense, LA UNIÓ calls for an increase in the requirements and controls at source, since detections of this fungus are skyrocketing.
